(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number null :title "Reference — the Challenges Appendix" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/00-cover.md" :size 4934 :sha256 "e4392a7e7cd9c17a" :content "---\nslug: book-reference-cover\nbook: reference\nchapter: 0\ntitle: Reference — the Challenges Appendix\npart: appendix\nof: reference-manual\napp: none\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane AJ)\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-10\npalette:\n  background: canvas-cream\n  top-band: magic\n  center: canvas-mint\n  ink: warm-plum\n  pink: sakura-pink (Sakura only)\nprev: null\nnext: 01-conway\n---\n\n# Reference — the Challenges Appendix\n\n*The computer-science-in-Scheme cookbook that lives at the end of the reference manual.*\n\nThe reference manual body — sections 1 through 20 of `scheme-lang/docs/SAKURA-SCHEME-1.0.REF.md` — is a dictionary. Every verb, every atom, every primitive is listed with its arity, its types, and its shape. That is the catalog.\n\nThis is the *cookbook*. It sits at the end of the reference manual as its final appendix, and it teaches Sakura Scheme the way SICP taught Scheme — through problems, not through paragraphs. Each chapter picks one canonical CS problem and works it end to end in runnable Scheme, showing the guts of the language while it goes.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> The catalog tells you *what* every verb does. The appendix tells you *how to think in the language*. Both matter. If you only read the catalog, you know the words but not the grammar of thought. If you only read the appendix, you have the grammar but keep having to guess at the words. Read them together — the catalog on one screen, this appendix on the other.\n\n## Voice and pace\n\n- Slow ramp. Each chapter starts small and builds.\n- Every fenced Scheme block is a standalone runnable program. Paste any block into `sakura-scheme repl` and it will produce the output shown below it.\n- CS-guts, not verb-operations. The point is the algorithm and the language feature it exercises, not \"how to call an API.\"\n- Random-access. You can jump straight to Chapter 3 (tail recursion) or Chapter 4 (macros) without reading the ones before. The chapters share a voice, not a state.\n- Fun. This is the \"become-amazing-at-one-thing\" appendix. Each chapter should leave you saying \"oh, I get it now.\"\n\n## The chapters\n\n- Chapter 1 — **Conway's Game of Life.** Grids, neighborhood counts, generation ticks. The first classic.\n- Chapter 2 — **Sorting, visualized.** Bubble, insertion, quicksort — with a dot-matrix trace so the compares and swaps are visible.\n- Chapter 3 — **Tail recursion.** Proof by example that the fast path is fast. Fibonacci accumulator, list-length, tree-sum.\n- Chapter 4 — **Macros.** Writing your own control form: `unless`, `swap!`, a mini `for-each` over ranges.\n- Chapter 5 — **A tiny metacircular evaluator.** Scheme in Scheme, SICP-style — the smallest interpreter that can evaluate its own hello-world.\n\nLater chapters (6 through 16, when authored) walk the rest of the CS canon: closures and streams, persistent data structures, state machines, memoization, small Turing-flavored things, the glorious finale.\n\n## Reading order\n\nThe chapters are graded intermediate → advanced → expert but each stands alone. If you know Conway already, skip to sorting. If you've never written a macro, spend a while on Chapter 4 — the chapter is worked in small steps and the last program in it is a real macro you can use in your own carts.\n\n> **Tip**\n>\n> Every program in the appendix is short enough to hold in your head. If a program starts feeling too long, that is the point at which it is factored into a helper — the appendix demonstrates factoring, not sprawl. When you get stuck writing your own, look at the shape of the helpers and factor along the same lines.\n\n> **Warning**\n>\n> Some of the programs use verbs that are documented in the reference manual body but not in this appendix. If you hit a verb you don't recognize, look it up in section 15 or 16 of the main reference. The appendix and the body are meant to be read side by side.\n\n## What this appendix is for\n\nTwo audiences:\n\n1. **The reader who wants to learn Scheme well.** You come out the other end able to write a Conway-of-your-own, a sort-of-your-own, a macro-of-your-own — and to reason about *why* those programs work.\n2. **The training corpus.** These programs and their reasoning voice are training data for the on-device Sakura model. The prose around each program is not decoration; it teaches the model to reason about its own code in a specific voice. That is why the programs are so heavily narrated.\n\nBoth audiences get the same book.\n\n## Cross-references\n\n- `scheme-lang/docs/SAKURA-SCHEME-1.0.REF.md` §15 — atomic primitives dictionary. Every atom used in these chapters is documented there.\n- `scheme-lang/docs/SAKURA-SCHEME-1.0.REF.md` §16 — special forms.\n- [[book-of-donts]] — the sibling appendix in the sixteen; the *defensive* book.\n- [[book-of-systems]] — where these algorithmic techniques get applied to real automations.\n\n---\n\n*Turn the page for Chapter 1 — Conway's Game of Life.*\n")
